00:46:42.480 --> 00:46:44.195
AUDIENCE: How
likely do you think

00:46:44.195 --> 00:46:46.400
it is that the
college system will

00:46:46.400 --> 00:46:50.111
exist in its current
form in about 15 years?

00:46:50.111 --> 00:46:51.860
RON LIEBER: I think
it's extremely likely,

00:46:51.860 --> 00:46:55.580
because snobbery.

00:46:55.580 --> 00:46:58.789
These brands are going
to continue to matter,

00:46:58.789 --> 00:47:00.330
and I think they're
going to continue

00:47:00.330 --> 00:47:02.050
to matter to a lot of people.

00:47:02.050 --> 00:47:04.030
And parents who,
for better or worse,

00:47:04.030 --> 00:47:07.090
aspire to great
things for their kids

00:47:07.090 --> 00:47:09.460
are just not to
be able to resist.

00:47:09.460 --> 00:47:13.980
A, the data that just shows that
people who go to college out

00:47:13.980 --> 00:47:16.450
earn people who don't--
no matter where they go--

00:47:16.450 --> 00:47:19.300
out earn people who don't buy
like zillions of dollars over

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:20.220
their lifetime.

00:47:20.220 --> 00:47:23.150
The numbers are
just off the charts.

00:47:23.150 --> 00:47:25.190
So kids will keep going.

00:47:25.190 --> 00:47:28.890
And parents who want to wear
the better-than-new sweatshirt

00:47:28.890 --> 00:47:30.780
and put the sticker
on their car are

00:47:30.780 --> 00:47:34.210
going to have a really hard
time tacking against that

00:47:34.210 --> 00:47:39.250
to send their kid
a MOOC or to have

00:47:39.250 --> 00:47:42.885
them do a certificate
for this trade

00:47:42.885 --> 00:47:44.500
or that trade or that skill.

00:47:44.500 --> 00:47:48.020
Even if it's taking
the 18-year-old who's

00:47:48.020 --> 00:47:50.370
obsessed with developing
apps and putting them

00:47:50.370 --> 00:47:56.880
straight into a hardcore coding
class for 12 or 18 months.

00:47:56.880 --> 00:47:59.460
For some kids, that may be,
in fact, the best thing.

00:47:59.460 --> 00:48:02.790
But it takes a lot of guts
to do something really,

00:48:02.790 --> 00:48:03.900
really different.

00:48:03.900 --> 00:48:06.300
18 years ago or
something, I wrote a book

00:48:06.300 --> 00:48:09.410
about taking gap
years from college

00:48:09.410 --> 00:48:12.520
and how that is so
clearly a better way

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:15.975
to approach higher education,
i.e., starting at 19 and not

00:48:15.975 --> 00:48:19.450
at 18 when you're still trying
to fine tune your personality

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:21.520
and you're out of the
house for the first time.

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:24.161
And even to this day,
it's not mainstream,

00:48:24.161 --> 00:48:26.410
even though that's how the
rest of the developed world

00:48:26.410 --> 00:48:27.150
does things.

00:48:27.150 --> 00:48:29.010
Kids don't go to college at 18.

00:48:29.010 --> 00:48:31.250
They do military
service, or they

00:48:31.250 --> 00:48:33.750
take some sort of a gap year.

00:48:33.750 --> 00:48:35.220
It still hasn't
hit the mainstream.

00:48:35.220 --> 00:48:37.260
So even if we do come
up with a better way

00:48:37.260 --> 00:48:39.500
to do this, a
cheaper way, I just

00:48:39.500 --> 00:48:42.390
think it's going to take a
long time for it to set in.

00:48:42.390 --> 00:48:45.480
And I get that there are other
changes in the world, changes

00:48:45.480 --> 00:48:48.660
that this company has
brought to the world that

00:48:48.660 --> 00:48:53.640
have been way more quick than
what I'm predicting will happen

00:48:53.640 --> 00:48:54.690
with higher education.

00:48:54.690 --> 00:48:57.930
But I just don't see these
institutions crumbling anytime

00:48:57.930 --> 00:49:02.310
soon, particularly the
top 50 or 100 or 150

00:49:02.310 --> 00:49:04.670
that many parents just
can't help but aspire

00:49:04.670 --> 00:49:06.250
to for their children.

00:49:06.250 --> 00:49:08.920
And also, we should keep in mind
that the kids play a role here,

00:49:08.920 --> 00:49:09.420
too.

00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:11.250
They bat their eyes
at us and they say,

00:49:11.250 --> 00:49:12.954
but this is what I really want.

00:49:12.954 --> 00:49:14.370
And it's like, are
we really going

00:49:14.370 --> 00:49:17.320
to, in this really
important moment,

00:49:17.320 --> 00:49:20.870
deny them the thing that they
most want for their next four

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:24.250
years, even though we think they
may need something different?

00:49:24.250 --> 00:49:25.950
It will be very,
very difficult, I

00:49:25.950 --> 00:49:30.640
think, for many of us to say
no and do something else.

00:49:30.640 --> 00:49:31.620
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:49:31.620 --> 00:49:34.385
I really love the idea of
engaging honestly and directly

00:49:34.385 --> 00:49:36.260
with kids about the
numbers that are actually

00:49:36.260 --> 00:49:39.970
involved in terms of the
family salaries and the family

00:49:39.970 --> 00:49:41.270
expenses.

00:49:41.270 --> 00:49:43.880
But how do you talk to kids
about that in a truthful way

00:49:43.880 --> 00:49:47.424
without having to be overwhelmed
by the difference in magnitude

00:49:47.424 --> 00:49:49.715
between the numbers that are
going on in a family level

00:49:49.715 --> 00:49:52.390
and what's going on at their
individual allowance or savings

00:49:52.390 --> 00:49:52.940
level?

00:49:52.940 --> 00:49:55.880
Why should they have
to sweat and slave

00:49:55.880 --> 00:50:00.270
to put away $10, $20 to buy this
toy when Mommy and Daddy are

00:50:00.270 --> 00:50:02.900
making so much more
money and spending

00:50:02.900 --> 00:50:04.390
so much money on vacations.

00:50:04.390 --> 00:50:06.789
Oh, this is how much it costs
for us to go to Florida.

00:50:06.789 --> 00:50:07.330
That's silly.

00:50:07.330 --> 00:50:09.371
Why don't we just tack a
tiny little bit more on,

00:50:09.371 --> 00:50:10.505
and we can all get Barbies.

00:50:13.300 --> 00:50:14.800
RON LIEBER: Much
depends on what you

00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:16.980
want to make them
responsible for and when

00:50:16.980 --> 00:50:19.180
you want to introduce
them to those big numbers.

00:50:19.180 --> 00:50:22.790
So I believe in doing
this really gradually.

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:24.599
And I do think you
should be transparent,

00:50:24.599 --> 00:50:26.390
but I don't think you
should be transparent

00:50:26.390 --> 00:50:28.340
until they are ready,
until they have the math

00:50:28.340 --> 00:50:31.120
skills, until they have
the context, until they

00:50:31.120 --> 00:50:32.967
have the experience of
doing it themselves.

00:50:32.967 --> 00:50:35.300
AUDIENCE: So until they're
making those kind of salaries

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:37.640
you're saying?

00:50:37.640 --> 00:50:38.890
RON LIEBER: No.

00:50:38.890 --> 00:50:42.400
Until they're able to reckon
with numbers that large.

00:50:42.400 --> 00:50:44.580
So if you think about
it on a continuum--

00:50:44.580 --> 00:50:48.940
you start at age six
or seven, and you're

00:50:48.940 --> 00:50:53.550
going along with the allowance,
and it's $5, $6, $8 a week.

00:50:53.550 --> 00:50:55.150
Maybe you increase it over time.

00:50:55.150 --> 00:50:57.070
Maybe the time they're
9 or 10 and they've

00:50:57.070 --> 00:50:59.360
been doing it for a while,
you sit down with them

00:50:59.360 --> 00:51:00.380
and say, you know what?

00:51:00.380 --> 00:51:01.963
A, we're not going
to pay for anything

00:51:01.963 --> 00:51:05.760
you want anymore, only at the
holidays and on your birthday.

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:08.100
And anything you want, you're
going to have to pay for.

00:51:08.100 --> 00:51:10.660
And we're going to increase
your allowance by 100%.

00:51:10.660 --> 00:51:12.660
But you're only increasing
it to the point where

00:51:12.660 --> 00:51:14.280
they can get a few of
the things that they want

00:51:14.280 --> 00:51:16.113
and not so much that
they don't have to make

00:51:16.113 --> 00:51:18.400
a lot of really hard choices.

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:20.050
And then, slowly,
you introduce them

00:51:20.050 --> 00:51:24.200
to bigger numbers-- the
grocery bill, maybe the rent,

00:51:24.200 --> 00:51:26.962
or the mortgage, all
the household expenses.

00:51:26.962 --> 00:51:29.170
In the meantime in the
background, they're in school,

00:51:29.170 --> 00:51:31.960
and they're now using four-
and five- and six-digit numbers

00:51:31.960 --> 00:51:32.700
in math class.

00:51:32.700 --> 00:51:34.500
So they're learning
more about that.

00:51:34.500 --> 00:51:36.291
They're getting used
to the bigger numbers.

00:51:36.291 --> 00:51:38.480
And you're saying
to them, look, this

00:51:38.480 --> 00:51:40.072
is part of our family's reality.

00:51:40.072 --> 00:51:41.530
There are these
three-digit numbers

00:51:41.530 --> 00:51:45.090
and these four-digit checks,
or electronic payments that we

00:51:45.090 --> 00:51:46.780
have to make each month.

00:51:46.780 --> 00:51:48.330
And so you may
think that we have

00:51:48.330 --> 00:51:50.720
a lot, because there are
all these big numbers

00:51:50.720 --> 00:51:51.630
floating around.

00:51:51.630 --> 00:51:54.640
But in fact, this is what
we need to spend in order

00:51:54.640 --> 00:51:56.240
to have the life that we have.

00:51:56.240 --> 00:51:58.960
And it turns out that
there's not a lot left over

00:51:58.960 --> 00:52:00.192
at the end of the month.

00:52:00.192 --> 00:52:01.900
And we're going to
tell you what that is.

00:52:01.900 --> 00:52:03.831
But first, you need
to understand--

00:52:03.831 --> 00:52:05.330
before we get to
the bigger numbers,

00:52:05.330 --> 00:52:07.520
you need to understand
what we're spending.

00:52:07.520 --> 00:52:09.639
And that takes years for
them to learn all that.

00:52:09.639 --> 00:52:11.930
Because if you did it all at
once, they would be bored.

00:52:11.930 --> 00:52:12.720
So you look for your moments.

00:52:12.720 --> 00:52:13.844
You look for your openings.

00:52:13.844 --> 00:52:16.290
You could spend a year
just walking the aisles

00:52:16.290 --> 00:52:18.400
at Whole Foods or Fairway.

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:20.300
Every single stop
in the grocery aisle

00:52:20.300 --> 00:52:23.684
is an intense lesson
in wants and needs.

00:52:23.684 --> 00:52:26.100
You've got environmental impact,
and you've got nutrition,

00:52:26.100 --> 00:52:27.650
and you've got social
responsibility,

00:52:27.650 --> 00:52:29.275
and you've got whatever
your budget is,

00:52:29.275 --> 00:52:31.450
and maybe you've
got some coupons.

00:52:31.450 --> 00:52:33.560
All this stuff-- each
of those decisions

00:52:33.560 --> 00:52:38.072
is its own kind of microcosm
of awesome trade-offs.

00:52:38.072 --> 00:52:40.530
So you could spend a whole year
in the grocery store alone.

00:52:40.530 --> 00:52:43.760
So then eventually,
13 or 14, by then,

00:52:43.760 --> 00:52:45.300
they've probably googled you.

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:48.290
They've googled your address.

00:52:48.290 --> 00:52:49.970
Maybe they've gone
to salary.com.

00:52:49.970 --> 00:52:52.530
Seriously, there are kids
who do this at 10 or 11.

00:52:52.530 --> 00:52:56.600
They've put software developer,
senior software developer,

00:52:56.600 --> 00:52:59.210
lead software developer-- they
look at your business card,

00:52:59.210 --> 00:53:01.251
they take that term, they
put it into salary.com,

00:53:01.251 --> 00:53:02.700
and they kind of figure it out.

00:53:02.700 --> 00:53:03.830
AUDIENCE: So kind of
like the sex talk--

00:53:03.830 --> 00:53:06.205
wait until they googled it
already, and you can avoid it.

00:53:06.205 --> 00:53:08.280
RON LIEBER: Well, that's right.

00:53:08.280 --> 00:53:09.740
They're figuring this out.

00:53:09.740 --> 00:53:12.510
They're getting the Zillow
estimate on your apartment.

00:53:12.510 --> 00:53:14.214
So they're starting to know.

00:53:14.214 --> 00:53:15.880
So at that point,
you're like, OK, look,

00:53:15.880 --> 00:53:18.310
we really do want to share
this information with you.

00:53:18.310 --> 00:53:19.551
In fact, you need it.

00:53:19.551 --> 00:53:21.800
It's important for you to
know what it is that we have

00:53:21.800 --> 00:53:24.370
and what it is that we make
that allows us to live and do

00:53:24.370 --> 00:53:26.260
wherever we live
and whatever we do.

00:53:26.260 --> 00:53:27.170
But we're not going
to give it to you

00:53:27.170 --> 00:53:29.294
yet, because you have to
prove that you can keep it

00:53:29.294 --> 00:53:30.442
to yourself.

00:53:30.442 --> 00:53:32.900
And we're going to check to
make sure that you are treating

00:53:32.900 --> 00:53:34.385
your friends'
information privately,

00:53:34.385 --> 00:53:35.940
and we're going to watch
you carefully to see

00:53:35.940 --> 00:53:37.610
if you're getting
conflicts there.

00:53:37.610 --> 00:53:39.259
We're going to watch
with your siblings

00:53:39.259 --> 00:53:41.550
if you have them to see if
you're reading their diaries

00:53:41.550 --> 00:53:45.880
or tattling on them
when they're not

00:53:45.880 --> 00:53:48.730
doing something that's dangerous
or worth tattling about.

00:53:48.730 --> 00:53:50.400
We're going to
keep an eye on how

00:53:50.400 --> 00:53:52.730
you deal with other
information, private information

00:53:52.730 --> 00:53:53.880
that the family gives you.

00:53:53.880 --> 00:53:55.970
And then we're going
to sit you down

00:53:55.970 --> 00:53:58.150
and say, OK, we're going
to tell you all of it now.

00:53:58.150 --> 00:53:59.410
You're 16, you're 17.

00:53:59.410 --> 00:54:01.300
10 years have gone by.

00:54:01.300 --> 00:54:01.990
You are ready.

00:54:01.990 --> 00:54:06.810
But if you tell anyone,
it will be a sign

00:54:06.810 --> 00:54:10.052
that we shouldn't trust you,
because you're not as mature

00:54:10.052 --> 00:54:11.010
as we thought you were.

00:54:11.010 --> 00:54:12.890
So this is a test.

00:54:12.890 --> 00:54:15.520
And by the way, if
you do tell people,

00:54:15.520 --> 00:54:18.350
it's not really going to
matter so much to them.

00:54:18.350 --> 00:54:20.220
Because maybe they
have a little more,

00:54:20.220 --> 00:54:21.636
and maybe they
have a little less.

00:54:21.636 --> 00:54:24.160
But they're just not going
to be all that interested.

00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:27.370
And if it turns that you're
like the zillionaire next door,

00:54:27.370 --> 00:54:29.390
and nobody knows it, and
you tell your kids that

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:30.973
and they blab about
that, then they're

00:54:30.973 --> 00:54:34.200
going to sound like jerks,
because their bragging.

00:54:34.200 --> 00:54:36.180
So no kid wants to
flunk the jerk test.

00:54:36.180 --> 00:54:38.330
No kid wants to flunk
the maturity test.

00:54:38.330 --> 00:54:40.420
And the kid wants to
use all this information

00:54:40.420 --> 00:54:42.870
in an appropriate way by
the time they're that old.

00:54:42.870 --> 00:54:44.020
And they want your respect.

00:54:44.020 --> 00:54:46.460
And so by then,
and only then, are

00:54:46.460 --> 00:54:48.560
they ready to get all
of that information.

00:54:48.560 --> 00:54:50.893
AUDIENCE: And that helps lead
into the picking a college

00:54:50.893 --> 00:54:52.100
major conversation as well.

00:54:52.100 --> 00:54:54.137
If you want to have
these same things,

00:54:54.137 --> 00:54:56.470
you need to make long-term
financial planning decisions.

00:54:56.470 --> 00:54:57.178
RON LIEBER: Yeah.

00:54:57.178 --> 00:54:59.720
Because most parents
think, well, gosh, they

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:01.380
worry, how on Earth
is my kid going

00:55:01.380 --> 00:55:04.050
to be able to
reproduce what I've

00:55:04.050 --> 00:55:05.420
been able to create for them?

00:55:05.420 --> 00:55:07.830
Because I didn't have a big
pile of student loan debt,

00:55:07.830 --> 00:55:09.580
and the price of
college was different,

00:55:09.580 --> 00:55:11.190
and I was lucky enough
to get hired at Google

00:55:11.190 --> 00:55:12.870
and work here or go
work for a startup

00:55:12.870 --> 00:55:15.610
before or after or in
between or whatever.

00:55:15.610 --> 00:55:18.080
But it turns out that there
are all sorts of kids who don't

00:55:18.080 --> 00:55:20.320
want what their parents have.

00:55:20.320 --> 00:55:23.650
Maybe they want to be artists,
or public school teachers,

00:55:23.650 --> 00:55:27.920
or start a small business that
doesn't involve technology.

00:55:27.920 --> 00:55:30.130
Maybe they want to be
artisans or mechanics.

00:55:30.130 --> 00:55:32.200
Or who knows?

00:55:32.200 --> 00:55:34.430
And so they may well
say to themselves,

00:55:34.430 --> 00:55:39.220
OK, well, if it took $220,000
in household income for us

00:55:39.220 --> 00:55:44.770
to have 2 and 1/2 a bedroom,
one bath apartment a mile

00:55:44.770 --> 00:55:49.410
from the Googleplex in New York,
maybe I can get by on $50,000

00:55:49.410 --> 00:55:51.714
a year if I lived in Bushwick.

00:55:51.714 --> 00:55:52.880
And I'll make that decision.

00:55:52.880 --> 00:55:53.421
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:55:53.421 --> 00:55:55.129
Thanks.

00:55:55.129 --> 00:55:56.670
PRESENTER: And just
time for one more

00:55:56.670 --> 00:55:58.630
question, and then
we'll stick around.

00:55:58.630 --> 00:55:58.768
RON LIEBER: OK.

00:55:58.768 --> 00:55:59.500
I'm happy to hang
around, though,

00:55:59.500 --> 00:56:00.820
if you want to do a one-on-one.

00:56:00.820 --> 00:56:01.320
Hi.

00:56:01.320 --> 00:56:01.640
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:56:01.640 --> 00:56:02.140
Thanks.

00:56:02.140 --> 00:56:03.530
This has been hugely valuable.

00:56:03.530 --> 00:56:04.770
RON LIEBER: Thank you.

00:56:04.770 --> 00:56:07.710
AUDIENCE: So I'm wondering--
in our household,

00:56:07.710 --> 00:56:09.250
we have two little kids.

00:56:09.250 --> 00:56:10.750
The older one is 4
and 1/2, so we're

00:56:10.750 --> 00:56:14.190
starting to teach the values
of wants versus needs, mostly

00:56:14.190 --> 00:56:16.620
around the topic of
tutus at this point.

00:56:16.620 --> 00:56:24.430
But the issue is the influx
of stuff from family members

00:56:24.430 --> 00:56:26.450
outside of our immediate family.

00:56:26.450 --> 00:56:30.000
And we're trying to teach
that goods are exhaustible.

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:33.686
That if you finish your
book of 1,000 stickers,

00:56:33.686 --> 00:56:34.810
that's the end of the book.

00:56:34.810 --> 00:56:38.700
But then we get a shipment from
the grandparents and the aunts,

00:56:38.700 --> 00:56:39.900
and et cetera.

00:56:39.900 --> 00:56:42.605
So how do you manage
those factors outside

00:56:42.605 --> 00:56:43.612
of your control?

00:56:43.612 --> 00:56:44.320
RON LIEBER: Sure.

00:56:44.320 --> 00:56:46.740
So on a very basic
level, you control access

00:56:46.740 --> 00:56:48.780
to the box cutter.

00:56:48.780 --> 00:56:52.150
So when the packages come,
you can open them out of view.

00:56:52.150 --> 00:56:54.170
You can open them after bedtime.

00:56:54.170 --> 00:56:57.270
You can put them away
for as long as you want.

00:56:57.270 --> 00:57:02.860
If the grandparents give you a
problem with that, well, tough.

00:57:02.860 --> 00:57:04.380
Because you're in charge.

00:57:04.380 --> 00:57:07.750
Now, the bigger issue
with grandparents

00:57:07.750 --> 00:57:12.200
is that they're a
menace generally.

00:57:12.200 --> 00:57:17.810
They exist to subvert every
last one of our rules.

00:57:17.810 --> 00:57:20.030
My brother and I happen
to share a mother who

00:57:20.030 --> 00:57:23.300
sent a black leather
miniskirt to our daughter

00:57:23.300 --> 00:57:25.310
when she was five.

00:57:25.310 --> 00:57:28.090
That went back to the store.

00:57:28.090 --> 00:57:30.230
So they love pushing
the boundaries.

00:57:30.230 --> 00:57:32.170
They take joy in it, in fact.

00:57:32.170 --> 00:57:34.450
It gives them glee.

00:57:34.450 --> 00:57:39.730
And so look, I would say-- I
literally had a sample chapter

00:57:39.730 --> 00:57:43.310
title in my book proposal that
said grandparents are a menace.

00:57:43.310 --> 00:57:45.750
But in fact, if they're not a
part of your day-to-day life

00:57:45.750 --> 00:57:47.300
or your week-to-week
life, if they're not

00:57:47.300 --> 00:57:49.216
your primary caregiver
when you're not around,

00:57:49.216 --> 00:57:50.680
say, or they don't
live with you,

00:57:50.680 --> 00:57:52.388
then I think you can
let some of that go.

00:57:52.388 --> 00:57:53.870
Although by all
means, parcel out

00:57:53.870 --> 00:57:57.520
the packages to whenever the
stickers are about to be gone,

00:57:57.520 --> 00:57:59.457
or they have been gone
for a little while.

00:57:59.457 --> 00:58:01.290
It's good that kids
love their grandparents,

00:58:01.290 --> 00:58:03.373
that they want to spend
time with the grandparents

00:58:03.373 --> 00:58:06.030
so that we can have
time to ourselves.

00:58:06.030 --> 00:58:08.770
But you're also asking
a bigger question

00:58:08.770 --> 00:58:11.550
there, which is that if you're
lucky enough to have more

00:58:11.550 --> 00:58:15.620
than you need, you
can, in fact, replenish

00:58:15.620 --> 00:58:20.561
the stuff as it goes away, and
they need not want or yearn.

00:58:20.561 --> 00:58:22.830
But you should make them anyway.

00:58:22.830 --> 00:58:24.940
Because patience is good.

00:58:24.940 --> 00:58:26.730
Yearning is good.

00:58:26.730 --> 00:58:28.480
You can even set a
benchmark for yourself.

00:58:28.480 --> 00:58:31.070
I talk about this in
the book a little bit.

00:58:31.070 --> 00:58:33.730
Some parents say, OK,
well, I think on average,

00:58:33.730 --> 00:58:40.720
I want my kid to be in the
30th percentile of stuff,

00:58:40.720 --> 00:58:45.192
or I want for every 10 kids
that my child is closest

00:58:45.192 --> 00:58:47.650
to, their 10 closest friends,
I always want my child to be,

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:50.440
on average, the seventh kid
to get whatever the kids are

00:58:50.440 --> 00:58:52.750
excited about-- so
the seventh Rainbow

00:58:52.750 --> 00:58:54.870
Loo, set, the seventh
set of Hunter boots,

00:58:54.870 --> 00:58:59.420
the seventh a Death
Star LEGO, whatever.

00:58:59.420 --> 00:59:01.220
Because then they wait.

00:59:01.220 --> 00:59:02.684
And it's good for them to wait.

00:59:02.684 --> 00:59:04.850
And quite often, by the
time the fourth or the fifth

00:59:04.850 --> 00:59:07.244
or the sixth kid has
gotten something, the first

00:59:07.244 --> 00:59:09.660
and the second and the third
kid are bored with that thing

00:59:09.660 --> 00:59:11.368
and are onto something
else, and your kid

00:59:11.368 --> 00:59:13.560
doesn't even need to get it.

00:59:13.560 --> 00:59:15.586
But again, it's good
for them to wait.

00:59:15.586 --> 00:59:16.710
It's good for them to save.

00:59:16.710 --> 00:59:19.880
It's good for them to pay
for things themselves.

00:59:19.880 --> 00:59:22.480
And it requires some
resistance on your part,

00:59:22.480 --> 00:59:23.480
but I think it's doable.

00:59:23.480 --> 00:59:24.313
AUDIENCE: All right.

00:59:24.313 --> 00:59:25.090
Thanks.

00:59:25.090 --> 00:59:26.250
RON LIEBER: Thank you.

00:59:26.250 --> 00:59:29.000
[APPLAUSE]

